          Additional informationPublisher’s note Springer Nature remains neutral with regard to jurisdictional claims in published maps and institutional affiliations.Extended data figures and tablesExtended Data Fig. 1 The field climate change experiment.In the long-term climate change experiment, warming (+3 oC), half precipitation (−50% precipitation), and double precipitation (+100% precipitation) are primary factors, which are nested with clipping as the secondary factor (all the 24 southern subplots are under clipping treatment). Thus, this experiment has twelve single and combined treatments, each with four replicates: Control (N), Warming (W), Half precipitation (H), Double precipitation (D), Clipping (C), Warming & Half precipitation (WH), Warming & Double precipitation (WD), Warming & Clipping (WC), Half precipitation & Clipping (HC), Double precipitation & Clipping (DC), Warming & Half precipitation & Clipping (WHC), and Warming & Double precipitation & Clipping (WDC). The site was established in July 2009. Surface (0-15 cm) soil samples were collected annually from all plots at approximately the date of peak plant biomass in the fall (September or October) from 2009 to 2020. Adapted with permission from ref. 26, Springer Nature Limited.Extended Data Fig. 2 Effects of warming on ARG composition and diversity.a, PCoA plots of ARG composition calculated based on Bray-Curtis dissimilarity coloured by sampling year with different marker types representing treatment conditions. b, Effect sizes of experimental warming on the rescaled diversity indices of ARGs, inferred from the metagenome sequences and GeoChip. c, Mean normalized ARG abundance categorized by host genus in control (C) and warmed (W) samples. d–e, Effect sizes of warming on the rescaled abundance of ARG groups based on host genus, inferred from metagenomics (d) and GeoChip (e). In b, d and e, data are presented as mean ± s.e.m. of the effect sizes estimated from linear mixed-effects models (n = 96 soils for b and d; n = 552 soils for e). Statistics: PERMANOVA (a) and two-sided Wald χ2 tests (Type II) (b, d, e); exact p values are shown in the figure for statistically significant comparisons; ***p < 0.001, **p < 0.01, *p < 0.05.Source dataExtended Data Fig. 3 Effects of experimental warming on ARGs carried by putative pathogens.a, The relative abundance of pathogen-associated ARGs for different drug classes. b, Effect sizes of experimental warming on the rescaled gene number proportion of ARGs carried by putative pathogens. c, Effect sizes of experimental warming on the rescaled abundance of multi-species ARGs carried by different hosts. d, Effect sizes of experimental warming on the rescaled abundance of multi-species ARGs of different gene families. Tet_MFS: tetracycline resistance MFS efflux pump, β-lac: β-lactamases. In b, c and d, data are presented as mean ± s.e.m. of the effect sizes estimated from linear mixed-effects models (n = 96 soils). In b, c and d, statistical significance was determined using two-sided Wald χ2 tests (Type II); exact p values are shown in the figure for statistically significant comparisons; ***p < 0.001, **p < 0.01, *p < 0.05, #p < 0.1.Source dataExtended Data Fig. 4 Warming enhances ARG mobility and intensifies pathogen-associated gene exchange.a, Effect sizes of experimental warming on the rescaled abundance of potentially mobile ARGs. Data are presented as mean ± s.e.m. of effect sizes estimated from linear mixed-effects models (n = 96 soils). Statistical significance was determined using two-sided Wald χ2 tests (Type II); exact p values are shown in the figure for statistically significant comparisons; ***p < 0.001, **p < 0.01, *p < 0.05. b, Bipartite network illustrating the sharing of identical ARG sequences between bacterial genera. Only ARGs shared between potential pathogens and their direct neighbours are included. Edges indicate the detection of an identical ARG sequence within a given genus, and ARG nodes (diamonds) connected to multiple genera (circles and squares) represent sequence-level overlap across hosts. Larger circles represent potential pathogens, while smaller squares represent non-pathogens. Node colours indicate taxonomic groups, while purple and green edges represent taxa-gene co-occurrences unique to warmed and control soils, respectively. Grey edges represent co-occurrences detected in both conditions. c, Alluvial plot showing the mean abundance of multi-species ARGs carried by putative pathogens. Section heights correspond to the mean abundance of ARG groups categorized by host phyla and gene families. Proteo: Proteobacteria, Tet_Efflux: tetracycline resistance MFS efflux pump, β-lac: β-lactamases.Source dataExtended Data Fig. 5 Diversity of bacterial communities cultured on antibiotic-containing media.a–d, Richness (a), Shannon diversity (b), inverse Simpson index (c), and Pielou’s evenness (d) of bacterial communities cultured on antibiotic-containing plates under control and warming treatments. Bars represent mean values and error bars indicate s.e.m. across replicate soil plots (generally n = 4 per treatment for each antibiotic plate; for tetracycline HCl plates, n = 3 for warming soils). Points represent individual plates. Warming effect sizes (βw) estimated from linear mixed-effects models are shown in the panels. Statistical significance was determined using two-sided Wald χ2 tests (Type II) based on all antibiotic-containing plates (n = 39 plates).Source dataExtended Data Fig. 6 Bubble plot illustrating differences in inhibition zone diameters of strains isolated from warmed and control soils.Each row represents an antibiotic, and each column represents a species. The top phylogenetic tree shows relationships between the 17 species. Orange bubbles indicate significantly smaller inhibition diameters under warming (p < 0.05, two-sided Wilcoxon rank-sum tests), indicating increased resistance, while blue bubbles indicate significantly larger diameters. Bubble size represents mean diameter differences.Source dataExtended Data Fig. 7 Comparing the inhibition diameters of (a) Aeromicrobium spp. (second column of Fig. 3d) and (b) Paenarthrobacter spp. (8th column of Fig. 3d) strains isolated from control and warmed soils.Violin plots show the distribution of diameters of each strain under different antibiotics. In the boxplots, hinges show the 25th, 50th, and 75th percentiles. The whiskers represent the maximum and minimum values, no further than 1.5 times the interquartile range. Numbers below the boxes indicate the number of diameter measurements. Statistical significance was determined by two-sided Wilcoxon rank-sum tests; exact p values are shown in the figure for statistically significant comparisons; ***p  < 0.001, **p < 0.01, *p < 0.05. Orange or blue asterisks indicate decreased or increased inhibition diameters under warming.Source dataExtended Data Fig. 8 Relationships between soil nitrogen contents and the relative abundance of Actinomycetota (a–b) or Actinomyceota-associated ARG abundance (c–d).Points represent individual soil samples coloured by sampling year (n = 96 soils). Black lines indicate predicted relationships based on the fixed effects of soil nitrate or ammonium estimated from linear mixed-effects models (LMMs) with sampling year included as a random intercept. The relative abundance of Actinomycetota (%) was calculated from 16S rRNA gene amplicon sequencing data. Actinomycetota-associated ARG abundance was estimated from metagenomic contigs and expressed as coverage depth per Gb. LMM’s r indicates the marginal coefficient of determination (pseudo-R2) representing variance explained by the fixed effect in the LMM. Statistical significance was assessed using two-sided Wald χ2 tests (Type II) (n = 96 soils).Source dataExtended Data Fig. 9 Ecological stochasticity driving ARG composition variations, estimated by Stochasticity ratio.Stochasticity ratios were calculated using the null-model-based stochasticity ratio (NST) framework. Bars represent mean stochasticity ratios and error bars indicate standard deviations estimated from bootstrap resampling of pairwise community comparisons. Underlying sample sizes were n = 1326 pairwise comparisons for control samples and n = 946 pairwise comparisons for warming samples. Differences between warming and control groups were tested using two-sided Kruskal–Wallis tests. Exact p values are shown in the figure for statistically significant comparisons; p < 0.01, p < 0.05, #p < 0.1.Source dataExtended Data Fig. 10 Linking temperature to ARG abundance.a, Principal component analysis of functional traits of isolated strains showing the clustering of ARG abundance with genes for high-temperature tolerance and nitrogen assimilation. b, Relationships between soil temperature and the relative abundance of Actinomycetota. Points represent individual soil samples coloured by sampling year (n = 96 soils). The black line indicates the predicted relationship based on the fixed effects of soil temperature estimated from the linear mixed-effects model with sampling year included as a random intercept. The relative abundance of Actinomycetota (%) was calculated from 16S rRNA gene amplicon sequencing data. LMM’s r indicates the marginal coefficient of determination (pseudo-R2) representing variance explained by the fixed effect in the LMM. Statistical significance was assessed using two-sided Wald χ2 tests (Type II) (n = 96 soils).Source dataSupplementary informationSupplementary Information (download PDF )Supplementary Notes 1–12 and legend for Supplementary Tables 1–9Reporting Summary (download PDF )Supplementary Tables (download XLSX )Supplementary Tables 1–9.Source dataSource Data Fig. 1 (download XLSX )Source Data Fig. 2 (download XLSX )Source Data Fig. 3 (download XLSX )Source Data Fig. 4 (download XLSX )Source Data Extended Data Fig. 2 (download XLSX )Source Data Extended Data Fig. 3 (download XLSX )Source Data Extended Data Fig.